http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Dance I-IV are two-semester courses designed for students with varied levels of ability and previous experience in the discipline. Dance students will demonstrate an ability to apply dance fundamentals and dance techniques in the production, performance, analysis, and critique of dance performance. Students are expected to perform in solo, small group, and large group settings. Dance students will critique performances and deeply reflect upon the impact of dance on culture as well as cultural influences on dance. Dance I, Dance II, Dance III, or Dance IV will satisfy the one-half credit fine arts requirement for graduation. Arkansas Department of Education approval is not required for Dance I, Dance II, Dance III, or Dance IV.
Creating
Students will generate and conceptualize artistic ideas and work.
Synthesize content generated from various stimuli to choreograph dance studies using original or codified movement
Examine personal preferences to create an original dance study that communicates an artistic intent
Students will organize and develop artistic ideas and work.
Analyze the manner in which the structure and final composition inform the artistic intent of an original dance study
Develop an artistic statement that reflects a personal aesthetic for an original dance study, using appropriate vocabulary
Students will refine and complete artistic work.
Evaluate the impact of choices made in the choreographic revision process using self-reflection and feedback from others
Refine a strategy to more efficiently and/or effectively record a dance
Performing
Students will analyze, interpret, and select artistic work for presentation.
Analyze dance studies and compositions that use time and tempo in traditional and non-traditional ways
Explore energy and dynamics as a means of interpreting movement phrases
Students will develop and refine artistic work for presentation.
Dance with sensibility toward other dancers while executing complex sequences to meet performance goals
Establish and break spatial relationships with others as appropriate for choreography
Apply body-mind principles and healthful practices to a range of technical dance skills for achieving fluency of movement
Initiate, collaboratively and independently, planned practice and rehearsal processes, with attention to technique and artistry informed by personal performance goals
Model leadership qualities (e.g., commitment, dependability, responsibility, and cooperation) when preparing for performances
Students will convey meaning through the presentation of artistic work.
Collaborate to design and execute increasingly complex production elements that intensify the artistic intent of a dance performance
Model proper dance etiquette during class, rehearsal, and performance
Responding
Students will perceive and analyze artistic work.
Analyze recurring patterns of movement that create structure and meaning in dance
Explain the manner in which dance movement patterns communicate artistic intent
Students will interpret intent and meaning in artistic work.
Compare the manner in which artistic expression and intent are achieved through the elements of dance by citing evidence from various dances
Compare the manner in which artistic expression and intent are achieved through the use of the body, dance technique, and context by citing evidence from various dances
Students will apply criteria to evaluate artistic work.
Apply artistic criteria to compare artistic expression in two or more dance performances
Connecting
Students will synthesize and relate knowledge and personal experiences to make art.
Review one's own choreography, developed over time, and its relationship to personal perspectives
Collaborate with others to identify questions that arise when preparing dance movement based on personal perspectives
Students will relate artistic ideas and works with societal, cultural, and historical context to deepen understanding.
Discuss the relationship of dance characteristics, techniques, and artistic criteria to the ideas and perspectives of the people from whom the dances originated
Describe the impact of cultural context on genres of dance
Discuss the opportunities available for dance as a vocation or an avocation
